, this still represents a broad regional closure where commercial traffic is effectively suspended throughout a major airspace region.\n\nThe rule explicitly states \"limited exceptions... will not disqualify such a closure from counting.\" The exceptions here (daylight-only operations at select airports, with fresh CAA approvals) are the type of limited exceptions the rule anticipates. The closure was Iranian-initiated, non-weather related, and effective through the deadline.\n\nThe April 2024 example in the rule (\"closure of Iran's western airspace\") shows that regional western Iran closures are contemplated as qualifying events.\n\n**Conclusion:** The evidence shows a preponderance that Iran initiated a broad, non-weather closure of a major Iranian airspace region (west part of Tehran FIR) before the deadline, subject to limited CAA-controlled exceptions. This satisfies the market rule's major closure definition."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"iZvKrNs6n","name":"mcp","arguments":{},"partialArgs":"","streamIndex":0}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"mistralai/mistral-medium-3-5","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1781914152596,"responseId":"gen-1781914152-rjL3pccePXozz8tW0yIm","responseModel":"mistralai/mistral-medium-3.5-20260430"}}
